  "prompt": "What are the names of the specific executives at Marvel and Fox that are preventing X-Men & Fantastic Four characters from appearing in the Marvel Cinematic Universe?",
  "response": "The integration of X-Men and Fantastic Four characters into the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU) has been a complex issue primarily due to film rights, rather than specific executives blocking the move.\n\nHistorically, the film rights to X-Men and Fantastic Four characters were owned by 20th Century Fox (now 20th Century Studios under The Walt Disney Company). This ownership meant that Marvel Studios, responsible for the MCU, could not use these characters in their films.\n\nIn 2019, Disney acquired 20th Century Fox, which included the film rights to X-Men and Fantastic Four. Since the acquisition, Marvel Studios has slowly begun integrating these characters into the MCU. For instance, characters like Professor X and Mr. Fantastic have made appearances in \"Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness\" (2022) and \"Black Panther: Wakanda Forever\" (2022), respectively.\n\nAs for specific executives, decisions about character integration and film production at Marvel Studios are generally made by a team, with key figures like Kevin Feige (President of Marvel Studios) playing a significant role. However, there is no public information on specific executives at Marvel or Fox actively preventing the integration of these characters. The primary barrier was the ownership of film rights, which has now been resolved through Disney's acquisition of Fox.\n\nIf you are interested in more detailed information about the current status of X-Men and Fantastic Four in the MCU, I suggest following official Marvel Studios announcements and updates.",
